For allegedly being responsible for a missing corpse deposited in the morgue of a clinic owned by one of them, two men, Chief Oladejo Edubi and Samuel Oluwatodimu have been arraigned before a Chief Magistrate Court, in Owo, Ondo State. Edubi and Oluwatodimu were arrested and arraigned before the court over the disappearance of the corpse of one Mrs Rebecca Ogunoye. The remains of Mrs Ogunoye was said to have been deposited at the Adeyemi Clinic in Isuada comminity in Owo Local Government Area of the state before it got missing. Edubi is said to be the owner of the mortuary while Oluwatodimu is the mortuary attendant. The duo were brought before the court on a three-count charge of conspiracy to commit misdemeanour, indecently interfered with a corpse and disposed off, of the corpse without the consent of the family. According to the police prosecutor, Inspector Owolabi Edu, the offence was contrary to and punishable under Sections 517, 242 and 249 of the Criminal Code Cap 37 Vol.1 Laws of Ondo State,2006. When the charge was read to them, the defendants ,however, pleaded not guilty to all the charges. While praying the court to grant the defendants bail , their counsel , Mr Osaze Uwadie, described such as their constitutional right but at the discretion of the court. The Chief Magistrate, Mrs Olubunmi Dosunmu,in her ruling, granted the defendants bail to the tune of N200,000.00 each and one surety in the like sum . Dosunmu also, ordered that the clinic should not admit any new copse for embalmment in the morgue pending the determination of the substantive case. The court equally ordered that the comprehensive list of already deposited corpses should be forwarded to the registrar of the court and adjourned the case till the June 10, 2020 for further hearing.